<div id="review_1899542843" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1899542843" />
    <a title="William" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1118264-william"><img alt="William" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1899542843?book_show_action=true">Feb 01, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="William" class="user" itemprop="url" name="William" href="/user/show/1118264-william">William</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1899542843" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8637198541205010282">I had a hard time getting used to the style and the presentation as laid down in the first few chapters, but around chapter five the magic appeared and that is where things began to get interesting. What&apos;s more is that all of the spells and the artefacts (perhaps with the exception of the broom) were new to me, as was the use of the &quot;secret passages&quot; to aid Ben in moving about the castle.<br/><br/>But what I really liked, in reflection, were all of the &quot;moral lessons&quot; that Ben learned as she lived those t</span>
  <span id="freeText8637198541205010282" style="display:none">I had a hard time getting used to the style and the presentation as laid down in the first few chapters, but around chapter five the magic appeared and that is where things began to get interesting. What's more is that all of the spells and the artefacts (perhaps with the exception of the broom) were new to me, as was the use of the "secret passages" to aid Ben in moving about the castle.<br /><br />But what I really liked, in reflection, were all of the "moral lessons" that Ben learned as she lived those two years after her parent's death. Things like duty and responsibility, of dedication to one's cause, the power of love and of (literally, in some cases) following your dreams. Also warnings to avoid prejudice, bad first impressions, and jumping to conclusions.<br /><br />Overall enjoyable, though I would have liked to have more use of magic and the learning of the same, as well as answers to questions that I had, like who (or what) provided the inner-voices / dreams experienced by Renaldo, Florian, and Ben. Perhaps in the sequel?</span>
  <a data-text-id="8637198541205010282" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


